title: For Sale:  Springfield US Model 1866 "Second Allin" Trapdoor
location: Lake Wylie, South Carolina, United States
postcontent: The Springfield US Model 1866 "Second Allin" Trapdoor .50 caliber Rifle, was modified from the .58 caliber Springfield Model 1863 musket. The exact number of Model 1866 Rifles produced (modified) is not entirely clear although the estimate is only around 25,000. When the Model 1866 was eventually replaced a few years later with the US Model 1868 Rifle, most of the existing Model 1866 Rifles were purchased by the Remington Arms Company and were resold to the French for use during the Franco-Prussian War of 1870-1871. While some of these rifles made it back to the United States over the years, the majority did not, making the Model 1866 a historically significant and very scarce example of American military firearms design. Rates Good to Very Good condition, especially for being 154 years old, and is probably one of the best you will find! Amazing to think this rifle, as a musket, was quite possibly used in the Civil War! Very sharp markings on barrel, breechblock, and has (2) inspector cartouches on left side of stock. Very fine example of an early AMERICAN military rifle! See photos. Layaway available. Contact me to discuss options. No FFL required. I ship directly to you once copy of driver's license is received to verify age. $50 flat fee Ground shipping. As with all antique weapons, an inspection by a gunsmith is recommended before attempting to fire.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1891 Argentine Mauser
postcontent: I have for sale or trade an 1891 Argentine Mauser made by Ludwig-Loewe of Berlin in 1894. Still chambered in the original 7.65x53 Argentine. All matching #'s except the bolt though the bolt is only about 20 numbers off and still in the same K serial prefix. No import marks and it retains the Argentine crest on the receiver which is quite uncommon, more common on carbines than on the rifles. The stock has been refinished at some point but was done well. Also this rifle is what some call a "parade rifle" and is priced accordingly. I have no provenance to prove that these guns that are called such were ever actually used as parade rifles and it very well could've been done by an importer or reseller. What this means is that the bolt, bolt stop, butt plate, barrel bands, magazine, and cleaning rod have had the bluing polished off and are in the "white." It does look quite good this way and while the barrel and receiver are the only parts retaining blue the bluing is quite good and there is no pitting anywhere above or below the stock line. Bore is good, not perfect but good and it shoots as well as you can expect a 123 year old rifle to shoot. I have 60 rounds of PPU ammo and 76 pieces of assorted brass (60 pieces PPU and 16 pieces I formed from Remington 8mm Mauser brass) along with a set of Lee dies I will include. I am looking for $350 for the rifle, dies, brass, and ammo.

title: For Sale:  Tec 9 (9 mm Semiautomatic)
postcontent: For sale a Tec 9 mm by Intratec. Orginally designed by a swedish company Interdynamics bult as the MP-9 submachine gun based on the design by the russian Carl Gustav and intended for millitary applications.  It's simple design, 5 pieces disassembly based on the toughnes and simplicity of the AK 47 made it a functionable military sub machine gun.  They did not find a goverment buyer, so it was redesigned and introduced to the US market as the KG-99.  This is a later version known as the TEC DC-9. It's in great gun, in great condtion with very little ware.  Has functioned fantastically as long as you keep it properly lubricated and cleaned (just like iny semiautomatic).  Has a case, 2 clips (32), a shoulder strap and a extension piece.  It is pre ban and meets all requirments as lond as the extension and large clips are not installed. This model was mostly known for it's use on the show "Miami Vice".  It's a fantastic handgun or some say sub machine gun.
